{"title":"Visual Semantic Reasoning for Image-Text Matching","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Image-text matching suffers because image representations from regional detectors or CNNs miss global semantic relationships among objects and stuff, limiting alignment to rich sentence-level concepts.","method":"Start from bottom-up region features (Faster R-CNN) and construct a fully connected relationship graph over regions where edge weights are learned pairwise affinities in an embedding space. Perform reasoning with residual Graph Convolutional Networks on this graph (using the learned affinity matrix) to propagate context and produce relationship-enhanced region features, without requiring external relationship annotations."},{"problem":"For matching a whole sentence to an image, one needs a holistic image embedding that captures key objects and high-level semantics while filtering redundant regional information.","method":"Apply global semantic reasoning by feeding the relationship-enhanced region features sequentially into a GRU with update and reset gates. The memory cell incrementally accumulates discriminative content and the final hidden state becomes the image representation. Regions are ordered (e.g., by detector confidence) to encourage effective accumulation; this gated memory over globally contextualized regions yields stronger whole-image embeddings for retrieval."},{"problem":"Pure metric learning may not sufficiently enforce that the learned image embeddings encode captionable semantics needed for robust cross-modal alignment.","method":"Jointly optimize a hinge-based triplet ranking loss with hard negatives in the shared embedding space (using simple inner-product similarity) together with an auxiliary sequence-to-sequence caption generation loss with attention on the same visual features. This multi-objective training encourages embeddings that are both discriminative for retrieval and predictive of captions, improving R@1 over training without the generation objective."}]}
